Clean Census Block Data¶

Step required to make the Housing Unit Allocation work.

Census Block Data needs to be combined with Census Place and PUMA data.

Initial Block Data provides state, county, tract, and block group information but does not identify the Census Place (City) or the PUMA (Public Use Microdata Area).

Census Blocks are used to define both Place Boundaries and PUMA boundaries. The geographies should be "nested" without any overlap between polygons.

Read in Census Block Data¶

Census Blocks provide an estimate of how many residiential address points (housing units) should be located in each block.

Program requires that user downloads the TIGER files for the state of interest. For example, Tennessee is FIPS code 47. The TIGER Block files for the state are located at https://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/TIGER2010BLKPOPHU/tabblock2010_47_pophu.zip

Once the files are downloaded, unzipped and saved, the files can be read into python.

In [32]:
census_blocks_shp = '../../SourceData/www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/TIGER2010BLKPOPHU/tabblock2010_47_pophu/tabblock2010_47_pophu.shp'
census_blocks_gdf = gpd.read_file(census_blocks_shp)

Note¶

EPSG 4269 uses NAD 83 which will have slightly different lat lon points when compared to EPSG 4326 which uses WGS 84.

Add Place Name (Cities) To Blocks¶

Read in place polygons for state and select places in study area¶

Place names provide link to population demographics for cities and places defined by the Census. The Census communicates with cities and updates city boundaries based on policitical boundaries set by communities.

In [52]:
# build the r-tree index - Using Representative Point
census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[census_blocks_select_gdf.index,'geometry'] = census_blocks_select_gdf['cbpnt4269']
sindex_census_blocks_select_gdf = census_blocks_select_gdf.sindex

# find the points that intersect with each subpolygon and add ID to Point
for index, place in select_area_census_place_gdf.iterrows():
    # print(place['NAME10'])

    # find approximate matches with r-tree, then precise matches from those approximate ones
    possible_matches_index = list(sindex_census_blocks_select_gdf.intersection(place['geometry'].bounds))
    possible_matches = census_blocks_select_gdf.iloc[possible_matches_index]
    precise_matches = possible_matches[possible_matches.intersects(place['geometry'])]
    census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[precise_matches.index,'PLCGEOID10'] = place['GEOID10']
    census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[precise_matches.index,'PLCNAME10'] = place['NAME10']

In [57]:
# Look at One Place plot the intersections and the city
oneplace_gdf_map = fm.Map(location=[(miny+maxy)/2,(minx+maxx)/2], zoom_start=10)
census_blocks_oneplace_gdf = census_blocks_select_gdf[census_blocks_select_gdf['PLCNAME10'].notnull()]
blockstyle_function = lambda x: {'color':'green','fillColor': 'transparent' }
placetooltip=fm.features.GeoJsonTooltip(fields=['NAME10'],
                                              aliases = ['Place Name'],
                                              labels=True,
                                              sticky=False
                                             )
fm.GeoJson(census_blocks_oneplace_gdf['geometry'],name='Census Blocks',style_function=blockstyle_function).add_to(oneplace_gdf_map)
fm.GeoJson(select_area_census_place_gdf,name='Census Places',tooltip=placetooltip).add_to(oneplace_gdf_map)
fm.LayerControl().add_to(oneplace_gdf_map)
oneplace_gdf_map.save(programname+'/'+programname+'_census_blocks_places.html')

Spatial Join PUMA ID to Block IDS¶

In [39]:

Out[39]:

Name: BLOCKID10, dtype: object
In [69]:
# build the r-tree index - Using Representative Point
census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[census_blocks_select_gdf.index,'geometry'] = census_blocks_select_gdf['cbpnt4269']
sindex_census_blocks_select_gdf = census_blocks_select_gdf.sindex

# find the points that intersect with each subpolygon and add ID to Point
for index, puma in select_area_census_puma_gdf.iterrows():

    
    # find approximate matches with r-tree, then precise matches from those approximate ones
    possible_matches_index = list(sindex_census_blocks_select_gdf.intersection(puma['geometry'].bounds))
    possible_matches = census_blocks_select_gdf.iloc[possible_matches_index]
    precise_matches = possible_matches[possible_matches.intersects(puma['geometry'])]
    census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[precise_matches.index,'PUMGEOID10'] = puma['GEOID10']
    census_blocks_select_gdf.loc[precise_matches.index,'PUMNAME10'] = puma['NAMELSAD10']

Save Work as CSV¶

A CSV file with the Well Known Text (WKT) geometry provides flexiblity for saving and working with files.

In [72]:
# Create Block ID String
census_blocks_select_gdf['blockid'] = census_blocks_select_gdf['BLOCKID10']
census_blocks_select_gdf['blockidstr'] = census_blocks_select_gdf['BLOCKID10'].apply(lambda x : "CB"+str(int(x)).zfill(15))
# Move Primary Key to first Column
first_cols = ['blockid','blockidstr']
census_blocks_select_gdf = census_blocks_select_gdf[
    first_cols + [col for col in census_blocks_select_gdf if col not in first_cols]]

Add EPSG 4326 Projection¶

The Census Buearu uses EPSG 4269 which uses NAD 83. However, the other inventories in the data structure use EPSG 4326 which uses WGS 84. The two projections may have some differences in the way Latitude and Longitude are determined. The differences appear to be minimal in practice.

In [73]:
census_blocks_select_gdf = census_blocks_select_gdf.set_geometry(census_blocks_select_gdf['geometry'])
